<h1>Pagination</h1>
<p class="text-muted mb-1">
  The gem doesn't paginate on its own (no surprise row limits). You paginate in
  the controller with your own gem — here
  <a href="https://github.com/kaminari/kaminari">kaminari</a> — and because a
  kaminari-paginated relation carries its page state,
  <code>crud_collection</code> notices and renders the footer pager
  automatically. The whole integration is two lines
  (<a href="https://github.com/itadventurer/crud_components/blob/main/test/dummy/app/controllers/pagination_controller.rb">controller</a>):
</p>
<pre class="bg-body-tertiary border rounded p-3 small mb-3"><code>@query = CrudComponents::Query.new(Book, params, fieldset: :index, ability: current_ability)
@books = @query.apply(Book.all).page(params[:page]).per(8)   # kaminari</code></pre>

<p class="text-muted small">
  120 seeded books, 8 per page. Filtering, search and sort still work — the
  pager's <code>?page=</code> is a plain GET param, so it composes with the
  gem's own filter params. Try sorting a column, then turning the page.
</p>

<% layout = params[:layout] == 'cards' ? :cards : :table %>
<div class="btn-group btn-group-sm mb-3">
  <%= link_to 'Table (gem footer pager)', url_for(layout: nil),
              class: "btn #{layout == :table ? 'btn-dark' : 'btn-outline-dark'}" %>
  <%= link_to 'Cards (kaminari default pager)', url_for(layout: 'cards'),
              class: "btn #{layout == :cards ? 'btn-dark' : 'btn-outline-dark'}" %>
</div>
<% if layout == :cards %>
  <p class="text-muted small">
    A custom layout can use the gem's footer pager, or its own — this cards view
    feeds <code>collection.page_scope</code> to kaminari's <code>paginate</code>,
    so the pager below is kaminari's default markup. Styling it is your job, as
    always with kaminari.
  </p>
<% end %>

<%= crud_collection @books, query: @query, as: layout %>
